Wash and dry all produce. Adjust rack to upper position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Bring a medium #pot of salted water to a gentle boil. Line a #baking sheet{} with #aluminum foil{}. Peel, halve, and finely mince @shallot{1}(finely minced). Thinly slice @garlic{4%cloves}(thinly sliced). Trim ends from @fresh pork chorizo{3%ounce}; peel off casings and discard. Cut meat into ¼-inch cubes.

In a small #bowl, whisk together @honey{1/2%ounce}, @olive oil{2%tsp}, @chili flakes{1/4%tsp}, and a few large pinches of @salt{pinch}. Halve @carrots{8%ounce} lengthwise. Place carrots on lined baking sheet and toss with honey mixture. Roast in oven until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

While carrots roast, melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium heat (use a #nonstick pan{} if you have one). Add @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup} and toss to coat. Toast, stirring every now and then, until golden, ~{3-5%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Remove from pan and transfer to a #small plate{}.

> TIP: Remove from heat if you sense any burning.

Once water boils, add @lobster ravioli{9%ounce} to #pot. Cook until just tender, ~{2-3%minutes}. Reserve ¾ cup ravioli cooking water, then drain. Meanwhile, add chorizo to pan used for panko over medium heat. Cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly crisped, about ~{5%minutes}.

Add @heirloom grape tomatoes{4%ounce}, shallot, and garlic to pan with chorizo. Cook, stirring every now and then, until shallot is just softened, about ~{3%minutes}. Pour in @sherry vinegar{2%tsp} and cook ~{1%minute}. Add @cream cheese{3%ounce} and ½ cup ravioli cooking water; stir until smooth.

> TIP: Add more cooking water, if needed, to create a loose, saucy consistency.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Gently stir ravioli and half the @parsley{1/4%ounce} into pan with chorizo and sauce. Divide between plates. Sprinkle panko over top. Serve with carrots on the side. Garnish everything with remaining parsley.